e. But she didn’t. Was that the right decision? Or had she just been too afraid? As days passed, this question stayed with her. Just because she could know something before it happened, did it mean she should change it? And if she did, what would the consequences be? She didn’t have answers, but she knew one thing—this ability was not just about observation anymore. It was about choice. One night, as she sat by her window, she heard something that felt different from everything before. It wasn’t just a sentence or a conversation. It was a warning. Clear, urgent, impossible to ignore. Someone was in danger. This time, she didn’t hesitate. She followed the feeling, moving quickly through the streets, trusting the direction without questioning it. When she reached the place, she saw exactly what she had sensed. A situation about to turn dangerous. Without thinking, she stepped in, her voice firm, her presence enough to interrupt the moment. It worked. The situation diffused. The danger passed. As she walked away, her heart slowly calming down, she realized something important. This ability wasn’t meant to give her control over everything. It wasn’t meant to let her rewrite every moment. But sometimes, just sometimes, it was there to give her a chance. A chance to act. A chance to help. A chance to make a difference. And maybe that was enough.
