        The night Aarush decided to stay late at the office was not supposed to be important. It was just another day that had stretched a little longer than usual, another set of unfinished tasks that needed attention. The building was almost empty by the time he finally leaned back in his chair, rubbing his eyes as the glow of his screen faded slightly. Outside, the city lights flickered in the distance, and for a moment, everything felt still. That was when he noticed something strange. On his screen, a file had appeared that he didn’t remember creating. It was simply titled “Tomorrow.” Curious, he clicked on it, expecting some forgotten draft or auto-saved document. Instead, what he saw made him sit up straight. It was a detailed log of events—meetings, conversations, decisions—all scheduled for the next day. His name appeared multiple times, alongside actions he hadn’t taken yet.

        At first, Aarush assumed it was some kind of joke. Maybe a colleague had created it as a prank, or perhaps it was generated automatically by some system he didn’t fully understand. But the more he read, the more specific it became. It mentioned exact phrases he would say, exact reactions from others, even small details like the coffee he would accidentally spill during a meeting. It was too precise to ignore. He decided to test it. The next morning, he deliberately tried to act differently. When a colleague greeted him, he responded with a different sentence than the one written in the file. But instead of changing the outcome, something unexpected happened—the conversation subtly shifted until it still led to the same result described in the document. It was as if the path adjusted itself to stay aligned with what had already been written.

        This realization unsettled him more than anything else. If the events were already fixed, then what did his choices even mean? Over the next few hours, he tried again and again to break the pattern. He skipped a meeting, avoided certain people, even left the office for a while. But every action seemed to circle back, reconnecting with the sequence described in the file. It wasn’t forcing him to act—it was simply… ahead of him. Watching him. Predicting him. Or maybe something even more disturbing—it was defining him. By the afternoon, Aarush felt a growing sense of unease. He couldn’t tell whether he was making decisions or simply following a script he had already read.

        That evening, he returned to his desk and opened the file again. It had updated. Now it included events for the following day. And the next. Each entry was as detailed as before, mapping out conversations, outcomes, even emotions. Aarush stared at the screen, trying to process what it meant. If he continued reading, he would know everything that was about to happen. Every success, every failure, every moment of uncertainty. But at the same time, knowing it seemed to take something away. The surprise. The spontaneity. The feeling of actually living through those moments. He realized that the more he relied on the file, the less present he felt in his own life.

        After a long pause, Aarush made a decision. He closed the file and deleted it. For a moment, nothing happened. The screen returned to normal, as if the file had never existed. He leaned back in his chair, feeling a strange mix of relief and uncertainty. The future was unknown again. Unpredictable. And for the first time since he had discovered the file, that felt right. Because maybe life was not meant to be perfectly understood or controlled. Maybe its value came from not knowing what would happen next, from making choices without certainty, and from experiencing each moment as it came. As Aarush packed his bag and left the office, the city lights seemed different somehow—not because they had changed, but because he had. And for the first time in a long while, he was okay with not knowing what tomorrow would bring.
