        At first, everything felt normal. Dusty furniture. Empty rooms. The occasional creak of wood. Kabir moved through the house methodically, observing, analyzing, dismissing anything that could be explained. The wind caused that sound. The floorboards caused that movement. Everything had a reason. He even laughed at himself at one point, realizing how predictable it all was. Then he reached the staircase. It led to the upper floor, where the rooms were darker, quieter. He hesitated for a moment, then continued.

        Upstairs, the air felt different. Not colder, not warmer—just… still. Too still. Kabir walked into one of the rooms, shining his flashlight around. Empty. Nothing unusual. Then he noticed something on the wall. Marks. Faint, almost invisible, but there. Lines. Patterns. As if someone had been counting something. He stepped closer, trying to understand. That’s when he heard it. A soft sound. Behind him. He turned quickly. Nothing. Just the empty hallway.

        He shook his head. “Wind,” he said quietly. But even as he said it, he knew it didn’t feel like wind. He stepped out of the room and continued down the hallway. Each step felt louder than it should. Each movement echoed slightly longer. Then he heard it again. This time clearer. Footsteps. Not his own. Slower. Slightly out of sync. Kabir stopped walking. The sound stopped too. Silence returned.

        He took another step. The sound followed. One step behind. Always one step behind. Kabir’s rational mind struggled to keep up. This didn’t make sense. There had to be an explanation. There had to be. He turned around suddenly. Nothing. Empty hallway. No one there. But the feeling remained. That quiet certainty that something was just out of sight. Just beyond perception. And as he stood there, trying to convince himself it was nothing, he heard a voice. Soft. Almost a whisper. Right next to him. “You’re not alone.”
