        The call came in just before midnight. Unknown number. Riya almost ignored it, but something made her answer. “Hello?” she said, her voice steady. There was no immediate response. Just silence. Then, faintly, she heard breathing. Slow. Uneven. “Hello?” she repeated, slightly louder this time. The breathing continued. Then a voice spoke. “You shouldn’t have answered.” The line went dead.

        Riya stared at her phone, unsettled. It was probably a prank. It had to be. She tried to shake it off, but the unease lingered. She locked her phone and placed it on the table. Minutes passed. Then it rang again. Same number. She hesitated, then answered. “Who is this?” she asked. This time, the voice responded immediately. “You’re alone.” Riya’s grip tightened. “Stop this,” she said firmly. “I don’t know who you are, but—” “Turn around,” the voice interrupted.

        Her heart skipped a beat. Slowly, she turned. The room was empty. Just as it had been. “There’s no one here,” she said, trying to sound confident. The voice laughed softly. “Not yet.” The line disconnected again. Riya stood there, frozen. The silence in the room felt heavier now. She walked to the door, checking the lock. Secure. Windows closed. Everything normal. And yet, nothing felt normal anymore.

        The phone buzzed again. This time, it wasn’t a call. It was a message. “Look outside.” Riya hesitated, then slowly walked to the window. The street below was empty. Quiet. Still. Then she noticed something. A figure. Standing across the road. Completely still. Watching her window. Her breath caught. The phone buzzed again. “Wave.” Riya didn’t move. The figure didn’t move either. Seconds passed. Then, slowly, the figure raised its hand.

        Riya stepped back from the window, her heart racing uncontrollably. This was real. This was happening. The phone buzzed one last time. “Now it knows where you are.” The screen went dark. The room fell silent. And somewhere outside, the figure remained. Watching. Waiting.
